NT|^B@2
Before I even counted the hand, when I just looked at it, I remembered the following guideline that I think is easy and important. Any time you have a 2-suited hand, with at least 9 cards in the 2 suits, and all your strength is concentrated in those 2 suits (as opposed to in your short suits), you should add 1 point to the value of your hand.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


NT|^B@2
And even 1 point might not be adequate. Hands with long strong suits, whether they be quality suits with at least 3 honors or not, will allow you to take more tricks than you would have thought based on your point count. If the hand turns out to be a misfit, then that is a problem.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Fortunately, although misfits are very annoying, they do not occur that often. Obviously, once responder bids 2NT, we know this hand is not a misfit.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


NT|^B@2
So let's get a count of opener's hand. 11 HCP, 1 point for the values concentrated in the 2 long suits, 1 point for the fifth spade, 1 point for the fifth club, so the starting total is 14. Now that partner supports my spades, I get 2 points for the singleton and 1 point for the long side suit. I am up to 17 points.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Don't lose sleep about the exact number. It is the overall concept that is key. So this is not a minimum hand. And I do have 2 1/2 quick tricks – that's a good thing. I will do the auction with the 4@C jump that most players would make. And then I will do the auction again with a 3@H shortness rebid by opener. So let's continue with the auction that starts 1@S-2NT-4@C. |
