^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|What happens if the auction begins 1@S-2N-3@H? A rebid of 3@H is a very reasonable thing to do even with the strong clubs. Now responder is extremely interested in slam. A singleton heart takes care of his one weak suit. So at this point, I would make an economical 3@S bid. |
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT|^B@2
It would not be crazy to bid 4@C as a control bid. But another bidding principle that I believe in is “When in doubt, make the cheapest reasonable bid.” You are allowing more room for partner to tell you about his hand. |mb|3sp|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT|^B@2
So, as North, I would bid 3@S over 3@H. Opener will bid 4@C to show a club control. Since responder has the @CK, he knows opener has the @CA. As responder, the singleton heart did so much for my hand that I could bid 4NT now. But what's my hurry? |mb|4cp|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT|^B@2
So over 4@C North would simply control bid 4@D. North is hoping his partner can bid 4@H. If he can, that would be awesome. Once you show a short suit, whether over Jacoby 2N or with a splinter bid, the only time you should bid that suit again is with a void. |mb|4dp|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT|^B@2
A singleton ace is not special enough to call for a second control bid. If you have a singleton ace and get to show your singleton, fine. Then if partner bids 4NT, you can show your ace with your Blackwood response. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT|^B@2
But do not control bid the singleton ace suit again. The second control bid in a short suit should be reserved for voids. If opener has a heart void, can you picture with responder's hand that a grand slam is very possible even if opener does not have a big hand?|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT|^B@2
On this hand, opener cannot bid 4@H. Opener does not have a terrific hand and does not want to force to the 5-level. So as opener I would just bid 4@S. This is not a sign off. It simply says “I can't do anything more. I deny a
big hand.” |mb|4sp|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT|^B@2
But responder, who already knows about the singleton heart and the @CA, is strong enough to bid 4NT. The auction will continue as in our prior auction. |mb|4np|
